PERFECT! The help says:"Excludes in_progress, blocked, deferred, and hooked issues."So `bd ready` does NOT return in_progress issues. That's good.But the spawn context says "Issue remained OPEN status with triage:ready label". So the issue status never changed from "open" to "in_progress", which means UpdateBeadsStatus is FAILING.Now let me create a probe file and investigate WHY UpdateBeadsStatus might be failing. Let me first check if there are any error logs from the daemon that might show this failure.Actually, wait. Let me re-read the daemon code more carefully. Line 856-860 shows:```go
if err := UpdateBeadsStatus(issue.ID, "in_progress"); err != nil {
    if d.Config.Verbose {
        fmt.Printf("  Warning: failed to mark %s as in_progress: %v (proceeding with spawn - tracker will provide fallback)\n", issue.ID, err)
    }
    // Continue with spawn - SpawnedIssueTracker provides secondary protection
}
```

So if UpdateBeadsStatus fails, the daemon CONTINUES with the spawn and relies on SpawnedIssueTracker. But SpawnedIssueTracker has a TTL and can expire or be lost on daemon restart!

This is the bug! The daemon should FAIL the spawn if UpdateBeadsStatus fails, not continue with fallback protection. The fallback protection (SpawnedIssueTracker) is fragile and can fail.Now I have a clear understanding of the bug. Let me create a probe file.

